  "market_context": "Asian session concluded, London session beginning; market sentiment bearish; price had already executed two liquidity sweeps (below equal lows, then above equal highs) before a sharp downside impulse created a Fair Value Gap.",
  "key_observation": "Price swept sell-side liquidity below prior equal lows, then swept buy-side liquidity above equal highs, followed by a strong bearish impulse forming a FVG—indicating inefficiency and high probability of downside continuation.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified the market phase as start of London session with bearish sentiment after Asian session consolidation.",
    "Step 2: Noted two liquidity sweep patterns: first run below equal lows to engage sell-side liquidity, then run above equal highs to engage buy-side liquidity.",
    "Step 3: Observed a sharp downward impulse move that broke structure and formed a Fair Value Gap (FVG) in the downside.",
    "Step 4: Concluded the FVG represented buyside inefficiency and signaled high-probability downside continuation.",
    "Step 5: Recommended short entries on pullback using multi-entry setups (e.g., wick/body/midpoint) within the FVG or prior supply zone."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Liquidity sweeps often precede directional continuation; a FVG formed after double sweep confirms institutional absorption and sets up high-probability counter-trend entries in the direction of the dominant structure.",
